column4: <content>[recto] BRVEGEL-RUBENS: A general rule: new features appear first as small scale subordinated parts of a picture. Still life, landscape added in window or background in XV becomes dominant in XVI. Painterly Bruegel's treatment of background landscape e.g. the plain in background in the right of the Babel Tower of Vienna with the trees brushed in irregular becomes a general characteristic of late Rubens landscape and an independent picture; [verso] Boston, Fine arts Museum (Glück 23) as e.g. in Birmingham, Barber Inst. Landscape (Glück, 23A) or much more decisive background ? as in N. Gall. Steen (Glück 30). Of course Rubens general also took over arrangement of landscape - as Glück has noticed.</content>
